JavaScript Object Protection:

- Object Protection Methods
    // Prevents re-assignment
    const car = {type:"Fiat", model:"500", color:"white"};

    // Prevents adding object properties
    Object.preventExtensions(object)

    // Returns true if properties can be added to an object
    Object.isExtensible(object)

    // Prevents adding and deleting object properties
    Object.seal(object)

    // Returns true if object is sealed
    Object.isSealed(object)

    // Prevents any changes to an object
    Object.freeze(object)

    // Returns true if object is frozen
    Object.isFrozen(object)


1️⃣ Using const:
    - The most common way to protect an object from being changed is by using the const keyword.
    - ⚠️With const you cannot re-assign the object, but you can change the value of a property, delete
        a property or create a new property.


2️⃣ JavaScript Object.preventExtensions():
    - 💡The Object.preventExtensions() method prevents adding properties to an object.

        const person = {
            name: "John",
            age: 30
        };

        // Prevent adding new properties to the person object
        Object.preventExtensions(person);

        // This will not add a new property
        person.email = "john@example.com";

        document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML =
        "Is person extensible? " + Object.isExtensible(person) + "<br>" + 
        "Person object: " + JSON.stringify(person);

        o/p:    Is person extensible? false
                Person object: {"name":"John","age":30}
    
    - 💡Since Array are objects, arrays can be prevented from extensions too.

        const myArray = [1, 2, 3];

        // Prevent adding new properties to the myArray object
        Object.preventExtensions(myArray);

        let text = "";
        try{
            // This will not add a new property, instead error will be thrown
            myArray.push(4);
        } catch (error) {
            text = "Error: " + error.message;
        }

        document.getElementById("demo2").innerHTML =
        "Is myArray extensible? " + Object.isExtensible(myArray) + "<br>" + 
        "MyArray object: " + JSON.stringify(myArray) + "<br>" +
        text;

        O/P:    Is myArray extensible? false
                MyArray object: [1,2,3]
                Error: Cannot add property 3, object is not extensible
    
    - ⚠️The Object.preventExtensions() method will fail silently in non-strict mode and throw a
        TypeError in strict mode.


3️⃣ JavaScript Object.isExtensible():
    - 💡You can use Object.isExtensible() to check if an object is extensible.
    - The Object.isExtensible() returns true if an object is extensible.

        
        const person = {
            name: "John",
            age: 30
        };

        // Prevent adding new properties to the person object
        Object.preventExtensions(person);

        document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML =
        "Is person extensible? " + Object.isExtensible(person);

        o/p:    Is person extensible? false


4️⃣ JavaScript Object.seal():
    - 💡The Object.seal() method prevents additions or deletions of new properties.
    - 💡The Object.seal() method makes existing properties non-configurable.
    - 💡The Object.isSealed() method can be used to check if an object is sealed.

        "use strict";

        const person = {
            name: "John",
            age: 30
        };

        // Seal Object
        Object.seal(person);

        // This will throw an error
        let text = "";
        try {
            person.email = "john@example.com";
            // delete person.name;
            // Object.defineProperty(person, "name", {
            //     configurable: true
            // });
        } catch (error) {
            text = "Error: " + error.message;
        }

        document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = text;   // Error: Cannot add property email, object is not extensible
    
    - 💡Since arrays are objects, arrays can be sealed too:

        // Create Array
        const fruits = ["Banana", "Orange", "Apple", "Mango"];
        Object.seal(fruits);

        // This will throw an error:
        fruits.push("Kiwi");
    
    - ⚠️The Object.seal() method will fail silently in non-strict mode and throw a TypeError in strict
        mode.


5️⃣ JavaScript Object.isSealed():
    - 💡The Object.isSealed() method can be used to check if an object is sealed.
    - The Object.isSealed() returns true if an object is sealed.

        // Create Object
        const person = {firstName:"John", lastName:"Doe"};

        // Seal Object
        Object.seal(person);

        // This will return true
        let answer = Object.isSealed(person);

        // Create Array
        const fruits = ["Banana", "Orange", "Apple", "Mango"];

        // Seal Array
        Object.seal(fruits);

        // This will return true
        let answer = Object.isSealed(fruits);


6️⃣ JavaScript Object.freeze():
    - 💡The Object.freeze() method prevents any changes to an object.
    - 💡Frozen objects are read-only.
    - 💡No modification, addition or deletion of properties are allowed.

        "use strict"
        // Create Object
        const person = {
            firstName: "John",
            lastName: "Doe",
            age: 50,
            eyeColor: "blue"
        };

        // Freeze Object
        Object.freeze(person)

        // This will throw an error
        person.age = 51;

    - Since arrays are objects, arrays can be frozen too:

        const fruits = ["Banana", "Orange", "Apple", "Mango"];
        Object.freeze(fruits);

        // This will trow an error:
        fruits.push("Kiwi");
    
    - ⚠️The Object.freeze() method will fail silently in non-strict mode and throw a TypeError in
        strict mode.


7️⃣ JavaScript Object.isFrozen():
    - 💡The Object.isFrozen() method can be used to check if an object is frozen.
    - The Object.isFrozen() returns true if an object is frozen.

        // Create Object
        const person = {firstName:"John", lastName:"Doe"};

        // Freeze Object
        Object.freeze(person);

        // This will return true
        let answer = Object.isFrozen(person);

        // Create Array
        const fruits = ["Banana", "Orange", "Apple", "Mango"];
        Object.freeze(fruits);

        // This will return true:
        let answer = Object.isFrozen(fruits);




    Object.seal()                                   Object.freeze():
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    You cannot add new properties                   You cannot add new properties
    You cannot delete existing properties           You cannot delete existing properties
    But you CAN modify existing values              You cannot modify existing values

    const obj = { name: "John" };                   const obj = { name: "John" };

    Object.seal(obj);                               Object.freeze(obj);

    obj.name = "Doe";     // ✅ allowed             obj.name = "Doe";     // ❌ not allowed
    obj.age = 30;         // ❌ not allowed         obj.age = 30;         // ❌ not allowed
    delete obj.name;      // ❌ not allowed         delete obj.name;      // ❌ not allowed
    